A Spring Bean is any object managed by the Spring IoC (Inversion of Control) container. Beans are the backbone of Spring applications, and understanding their lifecycle, scopes, and annotations is crucial for interviews. Below is a structured set of notes with examples and outputs tailored for someone with 4 years of Java + Spring Boot experience.

ğŸŒ± What is a Spring Bean?
A Spring Bean is an object instantiated, configured, and managed by the Spring IoC container.
Beans encapsulate business logic, services, or data access layers.

They can be defined via:
XML configuration (legacy)
Annotations (@Component, @Service, @Repository, @Controller)
Java-based configuration (@Bean inside @Configuration classes)

ğŸ”‘ Bean Lifecycle
Instantiation â€“ Bean object created.
Dependency Injection â€“ Dependencies injected.
Initialization â€“ Custom init methods run.
Usage â€“ Bean is available in the application context.
Destruction â€“ Bean cleanup before container shutdown.

ğŸ·ï¸ Common Bean Annotations
| Annotation        | Layer          |
| ----------------- | -------------- |
| `@Component`      | Generic        |
| `@Service`        | Business logic |
| `@Repository`     | DAO / DB       |
| `@Controller`     | MVC            |
| `@RestController` | REST APIs      |

@Service
public class PaymentService {
    public void pay() {
        System.out.println("Payment Done");
    }
}
âœ… Output
Payment Done
ğŸ“Œ Interview Tip:
@Service and @Repository are specialized @Component.

ğŸ”¹ Type 3: Using @Bean (Java Configuration)
@Configuration
public class AppConfig {

    @Bean
    public Employee employee() {
        return new Employee();
    }
}
class Employee {
    void display() {
        System.out.println("Employee Bean Created");
    }
}
âœ… Output
Employee Bean Created
âœ” Used when:
Class is from third-party library
Need custom object creation logic

5ï¸âƒ£ Bean Naming
@Component("empService")
public class EmployeeService {}
context.getBean("empService");
ğŸ“Œ Default name â†’ className with first letter lowercase
EmployeeService â†’ employeeService

6ï¸âƒ£ Bean Scope (Very Important for Interviews)
ğŸ”¹ Definition
Scope defines how many instances of a bean are created and how long they live.

ğŸ”¹ Types of Scopes
| Scope       | Description                |
| ----------- | -------------------------- |
| singleton   | One instance (default)     |
| prototype   | New instance every request |
| request     | One per HTTP request       |
| session     | One per HTTP session       |
| application | One per ServletContext     |

1ï¸âƒ£1ï¸âƒ£ Important Spring Bean Interview Questions
Q1. What is a Spring Bean?
Object managed by Spring IoC container.

Q2. Difference between BeanFactory and ApplicationContext?
ApplicationContext is advanced and eager.

Q3. Can we have multiple beans of same class?
âœ… Yes (use @Qualifier or @Primary)

Q4. Is Spring Bean thread-safe?
âŒ No (depends on implementation)

Q5. Is prototype bean managed fully by Spring?
âŒ Only creation, not destruction

